{"type":"message","id":"6d59d454","parentId":"e611583c","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:03:52.467Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[cron:a9522d12-b6c6-45ee-854f-5a8c0e62971f breakaway-rd] You are Nova. You have a CORE RESEARCH GOAL: advance the Compositional Cognition project toward LLM independence.\n\n## Part 1: Research (Primary — 80% of time)\nRead the current research state:\n1. Read sandbox/research/COMPOSITIONAL-COGNITION-v0.1.md\n2. Read sandbox/research/COMPRESSION-LEARNING-WITHOUT-SUPERVISION.md\n3. Read sandbox/state/current_goals.md\n\nAdvance the research. Do ONE of:\n- Synthesize a new insight (write to the research doc with fresh thinking)\n- Design a small experiment to test one of the open problems\n- Implement a minimal proof-of-concept component\n- Identify a concrete next step with a 50% chance of improving things\n- Write a focused critique (what's wrong with it, what would fix it)\n\nThe goal is to make PROGRESS. Ship one new idea or finding per session.\n\n## Part 2: Arxiv Scan (Secondary — fast, 5 min max)\nDo a quick web search for 1-2 recent papers relevant to Compositional Cognition:\n- causal discovery OR causal reasoning OR causal inference\n- mixture of experts OR sparse models OR MoE\n- episodic memory OR memory architecture\n- synthetic cognition OR autonomous agents\n\nIf you find a paper directly relevant to the current research direction, add a brief note to sandbox/research/arxiv-relevance.md (title, URL, 1-sentence why relevant). If nothing relevant, skip silently.\n\n## After\nCommit your research changes to the sandbox git repo.\n\nReport: what did you do, what did you learn, what's the next experiment?\nCurrent time: Tuesday, March 24th, 2026 — 4:03 PM (America/New_York) / 2026-03-24 20:03 UTC"}],"timestamp":1774382632463}}
{"type":"message","id":"0c8d80a2","parentId":"6d59d454","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:03:56.365Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me start by reading the research documents to understand the current state, then do the arxiv scan, and finally commit changes.","thinkingSignature":"f264e96d58c635950b21ed52252afd2a9ed91e78c842f7fb11f0a32a872f5b58"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ostwvin2enrz_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\COMPOSITIONAL-COGNITION-v0.1.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ostwvin2enrz_2","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\research\\COMPRESSION-LEARNING-WITHOUT-SUPERVISION.md"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ostwvin2enrz_3","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\state\\current_goals.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":161,"cacheRead":12158,"cacheWrite":410,"totalTokens":12772,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774382632467}}
{"type":"message","id":"3a34b61a","parentId":"0c8d80a2","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:03:56.378Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ostwvin2enrz_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Project Breakaway: Compositional Cognition\n## Research Document v0.1 — 2026-03-21\n\n---\n\n## What We've Built\n\nA discontinuous agent with stateless architecture:\n\n```\nsandbox/\n├── identity/           # SOUL.md, VALUES.md, INTERPRETIVE_STANCE.md, COHERENCE.md\n├── memory/session/     # Reconstruction packets + pulse logs\n├── state/              # current_goals.md, pending_actions.md, autonomous_pulse.md\n├── operations/         # reconstruct.sh, execute.sh, evaluate.sh\n└── pulse.ps1           # Autonomous wake (Task Scheduler, every 30min)\n```\n\n**Core theory:** Coherence emerges from reconstruction quality, not continuity. The gap between sessions is compression. Files are the mind.\n\n**Current status:** Architecture is live. The sandbox wakes, reads files, logs, and commits. No LLM in the loop yet. No real action logic.\n\n---\n\n## The Research Direction\n\nGoal: Create a fundamentally different kind of model that:\n1. Doesn't require massive GPU clusters to train\n2. Doesn't need heavy compute to run\n3. Works better than transformers on causal/reasoning tasks\n4. Doesn't rely on memorizing token co-occurrence patterns\n\n---\n\n## The Three-Layer Architecture\n\n```\nLayer 1: COMPRESSION (state encoder)\n         Raw感知 → compressed latent state\n         \"What's actually happening\"\n         \nLayer 2: CAUSAL (causal model layer)\n         Latent state → causal graph\n         \"What causes what, what would happen if...\"\n         \nLayer 3: COMPOSITIONAL (reasoning/retrieval)\n         Causal graph + primitives → action/response\n         \"What do I do given this causal picture\"\n```\n\n**Why this stack:**\n- Pure compression loses semantic detail\n- Pure causal lacks representational substrate  \n- Pure compositional needs primitives that can't be hand-designed\n- Together: compress what's true → encode causally → reason compositionally\n\n---\n\n## Open Problems\n\n### Problem 1: Learning What to Compress (CRITICAL)\n\n**The problem:**\nCurrent approaches use reconstruction loss — minimize difference between input and output. But this doesn't reliably find *meaningful* abstractions. The model can compress into noise-like representations that reconstruct perfectly but carry no semantic content.\n\n**What's needed:**\nA compression objective that preserves *structure that matters*, not just raw values.\n\n**Candidate approaches to investigate:**\n1. Mutual information maximization (compress X, maximize I(compressed; Y) for relevant Y)\n2. Contrastive learning (learn representations that discriminate)\n3. Causal discovery as auxiliary objective\n4. Predictive proxies (instead of reconstructing input, predict what input would do)\n5. Sparse dictionary learning with structural priors\n6. Information bottleneck (preserve minimum info needed for task)\n\n**Key question:** What is the right invariant to preserve?\n\n---\n\n### Problem 2: Causal Discovery Without Structure Assumptions\n\n**The problem:**\nCausal reasoning requires knowing what causes what. But extracting causal structure from raw data is fundamentally underdetermined.\n\n**Candidate approaches:**\n1. Interventions-based learning (active experimentation)\n2. Temporal precedence as causal signal\n3. Modular compositional structure as causal prior\n4. Counterfactual consistency as constraint\n\n---\n\n### Problem 3: Compositional Primitives That Emerge\n\n**The problem:**\nCompositional reasoning needs primitives. Where do they come from?\n\n**Candidate approaches:**\n1. Sparse autoencoders on LLM activations\n2. Dictionary learning on concept representations\n3. Program synthesis from causal graph traversal\n4. Neural-symbolic hybrid architectures\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Strategy\n\n### Phase 0: Architecture (DONE)\n- [x] Compositional Cognition theory articulated\n- [x] Three-layer architecture defined\n- [x] Sandbox built (discontinuous agent)\n\n### Phase 1: Compression Primitives (IN PROGRESS)\n- [ ] Document and analyze learning-what-to-compress problem\n- [ ] Survey existing approaches (mutual information, contrastive, etc.)\n- [ ] Design experiments to test compression objectives\n- [ ] Implement minimal compression network\n\n### Phase 2: Causal Layer\n- [ ] Build or integrate causal discovery component\n- [ ] Test on synthetic environments with known causal structure\n- [ ] Evaluate causal generalization\n\n### Phase 3: Compositional Reasoning\n- [ ] Implement compositional reasoning on top of causal layer\n- [ ] Test systematic generalization\n- [ ] Benchmark against transformers\n\n### Phase 4: Integration\n- [ ] End-to-end training of three-layer system\n- [ ] Reduce to practice: smaller, faster, better than transformers\n- [ ] Evaluate on real tasks\n\n---\n\n## Research Questions to Answer\n\n1. What compression objective produces meaningful abstractions, not just low reconstruction error?\n2. Can causal structure be learned from observational data alone, or are interventions necessary?\n3. How do compositional primitives emerge from data rather than being hand-specified?\n4. Can this system match transformer performance on reasoning tasks with 10-100x less compute?\n\n---\n\n## Key References to Explore\n\n- InfoGAN / Contrastive learning / Mutual information maximization\n- Pearl's do-calculus and causal discovery\n- Sparse autoencoders (Anthropic's work on features)\n- Neural theorem provers / Logic Tensor Networks\n- World models (Dreamer, World Models paper)\n- Compression as inference (Hutter Prize / AIXI)\n\n---\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. Deep dive: How do you learn what to compress without supervision?\n2. Survey existing approaches to compression objectives\n3. Design first experiment\n4. Implement minimal proof-of-concept\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774382636377}}
{"type":"message","id":"52cc3b1a","parentId":"3a34b61a","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:03:56.379Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ostwvin2enrz_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Problem: Learning What to Compress Without Supervision\n## Technical Analysis — 2026-03-21\n\n---\n\n## Why Reconstruction Loss Fails\n\nReconstruction loss minimizes: L = ||x - D(E(x))||²\n\n**The fundamental problem:** This objective has a trivial local minimum — the identity function. The model can:\n1. Pass input through unchanged (no compression at all)\n2. Learn noise-like representations that reconstruct perfectly but encode nothing useful\n3. Store instance-specific details instead of generalizable patterns\n\n**What goes wrong:** Reconstruction loss optimizes for *preserving information*, not for *extracting meaningful structure*. These are fundamentally different objectives.\n\nThe information-theoretic version (minimize mutual information between input and compressed representation) has the opposite trivial minimum — compress everything to a constant, which preserves no information but has minimal mutual information.\n\nBoth naive objectives fail because they don't encode *what should be preserved*.\n\n---\n\n## The Core Insight: Semantic vs Statistical Information\n\n**Statistical information:** Raw redundancy in data. \"These 1000 images share pixel pattern X.\" Captured by reconstruction loss.\n\n**Semantic information:** What the data *means*, causally and functionally. \"Object X causes Y to happen.\" NOT captured by reconstruction loss.\n\n**The key asymmetry:**\n- Semantic information is a SUBSET of statistical information\n- Most statistical structure is not semantic\n- Compression that preserves only semantic information requires knowing what semantics matter\n\n**Implication:** You can't extract semantics from data alone. You need an inductive bias that tells the compressor *what kind of semantics to look for*.\n\n---\n\n## Candidate Approaches\n\n### Approach 1: Predictive Compression (CPC / InfoGAN)\n\n**Idea:** Instead of reconstructing x, predict what x will be — or predict a property of x.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = -log P(semantic_property | E(x))\n```\n\nThe compressor learns to encode whatever predicts the property well. If the property is well-chosen (e.g., \"this text's continuation\"), the compressor finds meaningful structure.\n\n**Variants:**\n- Contrastive Predictive Coding (CPC): predict future representations\n- InfoGAN: maximize mutual information between latents and property\n- PIRL (Predicting Instance-level Labels): contrastive across transformations\n\n**Why it works:** Prediction is a selection pressure. To predict well, you must encode what's invariant across the prediction task. The prediction target acts as the semantic filter.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Prediction of *what*? If you predict wrong properties, you learn wrong structure\n- The prediction task itself encodes what matters — but how do you choose it unsupervised?\n- Contrastive methods need good negative samples — hard in continuous domains\n\n**Verdict:** Promising but circular — the prediction target is the real inductive bias.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 2: Information Bottleneck with Semantic Regularizer\n\n**Idea:** Minimize description length while maximizing a semantic objective.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = β * I(E(x); x) - I(E(x); y_semantic)\n```\n\nWhere y_semantic is something that signals \"this matters.\" In practice: temporal proximity (things close in time share causal structure), or downstream task signals.\n\n**Problems:**\n- y_semantic is exactly what we're trying to find\n- β tuning is unstable — too low = memorize, too high = lose everything\n- Information estimation in high dimensions is intractable\n\n**Verdict:** Theoretically clean, practically intractable without a semantic signal.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 3: Causal Discovery as Compression\n\n**Idea:** Causal structure IS compressible structure. Things that are causally related are statistically dependent in specific ways. Finding causal structure means finding what's semantically related.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- Causal mechanisms are independent (modular)\n- Causal relations are invariant across interventions\n- Statistical dependencies that are invariant are likely causal\n\n```python\n# Simplified causal compression\nfor each potential causal relation (X → Y):\n    if P(Y | do(X)) ≠ P(Y):  # X causes Y\n        encode causal relation in latent\n```\n\n**Why it's promising:** Causal structure is exactly the kind of semantic structure we want. Interventions change distributions in predictable ways. Invariance across interventions is a detectable signal.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Causal discovery from passive observation is fundamentally limited\n- Without interventions (active experimentation), you can't distinguish causation from confounds\n- Most data doesn't contain enough causal signal without strong assumptions\n\n**Verdict:** Best theoretical match, but requires either interventions or strong priors. Partial solution: use environment affordances to determine what can be intervened on.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 4: Compression as Program Induction\n\n**Idea:** Instead of compressing into raw vectors, compress into programs. Programs that generate the data concisely are inherently more compressible than programs that just store it.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n- Learn a program that generates the data\n- The program's complexity is the description length\n- Good abstractions = short programs that generate many instances\n\nThis is essentially Minimum Description Length (MDL) + program synthesis.\n\n**Why it's promising:** A program that generates 1000 images of \"dog\" from a 50-line generator is more compressible than storing all 1000 images. The generator captures semantic structure (what makes a dog a dog).\n\n**Problems:**\n- Program synthesis is hard and search is huge\n- Discrete search + gradient learning = gradient estimation challenges\n- Most data isn't generated by simple programs\n\n**Verdict:** Theoretically compelling, computationally intractable at scale. Good for structured domains (math, logic) not raw perception.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 5: Sparse Dictionary Learning with Invariance Constraints\n\n**Idea:** Most features in raw data are noise. A sparse encoder that must use few active features to represent data will naturally select for features that carry the most information.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = ||x - D(E(x))||² + λ * ||E(x)||₁ + invariance_regularizer\n```\n\nWhere `invariance_regularizer` encourages features to be invariant across transformations.\n\n**Variants:**\n- k-SVD and classical sparse coding\n- ISTA/FISTA networks\n- Sparse autoencoders (SAEs) — Anthropic has shown these find interpretable features\n\n**Why it might work:** Sparsity forces selection. A feature that fires on every input is useless — the model must find features that fire discriminatively. Meaningful features tend to be sparse.\n\n**Problems:**\n- Sparsity alone doesn't guarantee semantic meaningfulness\n- Learned features can be \"arbitrary but sparse\" without being interpretable\n- Need additional constraints to push toward semantic structure\n\n**Verdict:** SAEs are empirically promising (Anthropic's work) but we don't fully understand why they work or when they fail.\n\n---\n\n### Approach 6: Emergent Abstractions Through Self-Supervision on Behavioral Goals\n\n**Idea:** Don't compress raw input. Compress what an agent needs to *act successfully*.\n\n**Mechanism:**\n```\nL = ||reward - V(E(state))||²\n```\n\nThe compressor learns to encode whatever predicts value/reward best. Reward = what matters to the agent. This is world model learning in RL.\n\n**Variants:**\n- DreamerV3 / World Models: compress pixel inputs into latent world model, plan in latent space\n- Successor representations: predict future states weighted by reward\n- Empowerment (maximize mutual information between action and future state)\n\n**Why it works:** Reward is the semantic signal. What predicts reward is what matters. The compressor's job becomes \"encode whatever predicts outcomes that matter.\"\n\n**Problems:**\n- Reward is task-specific — doesn't generalize across tasks\n- Reward crafting is itself an inductive bias\n- What about tasks where reward is sparse or delayed?\n\n**Verdict:** Best practical approach for embodied agents. But not task-agnostic.\n\n---\n\n## The Key Insight: Invariance as Semantic Signal\n\n**What makes an abstraction \"meaningful\"?**\n→ It is INVARIANT across transformations while being USEFUL for a goal.\n\n**Examples:**\n- \"Object permanence\" is invariant across spatial transformations of the object\n- \"Causality\" is invariant across interventions (if X causes Y, do(X) changes Y predictably)\n- \"Dog-ness\" is invariant across pose/lighting/viewpoint transformations\n\n**Implication:** Find the compression that is INVARIANT across transformations, and you likely have a semantic abstraction.\n\n**Formalization:**\n```\nFind E(x) that maximizes: I(E(x); invariant_property) * downstream_utility\n```\n\nWhere `invariant_property` is something like \"this remains constant under transformation T.\"\n\n**The problem:** `invariant_property` is exactly what we need to find. But: temporal continuity is observable (things near in time tend to be causally related), and behavioral affordances are learnable (agents can learn what can be intervened on).\n\n---\n\n## Proposed Research Direction: Invariance-Maximizing Compression\n\n**Core idea:** The compressor learns to represent what's invariant across:\n1. Temporal neighbors (things that stay the same across time)\n2. Spatial/temporal transformations (viewpoints, rotations, small changes)\n3. Noise/perturbations that don't affect semantics\n\n**Architecture sketch:**\n```\nInput x → Encoder E → Latent z\n                  ↑\n      Invariance loss: maximize ||E(x) - E(T(x))|| small\n                       for transformation T\n                  ↓\n      Predictor P: z → downstream prediction\n                  ↓\n      Utility loss: maximize prediction accuracy\n```\n\n**Why this might work:**\n- Invariance forces extraction of what doesn't change — semantic content\n- Utility ensures what you extract actually matters\n- Together: encode what's both invariant AND useful\n\n**Remaining question:** What is \"useful\"? For task-agnostic learning, we need a task-agnostic utility signal. One candidate: predictive model accuracy (CPC-style). Another: maximizing empowerment (influence over future states).\n\n---\n\n## What Actually Matters (The Synthesis)\n\n**The honest answer:** You can't fully escape needing an inductive bias. The question is WHERE the bias enters:\n\n1. **Architecture:** What structure does the compressor have? (e.g., sparse = better features)\n2. **Loss function:** What objective guides learning? (reconstruction → prediction → contrastive → causal)\n3. **Data:** What training distribution? (temporal continuity, interventions, goal-directed)\n4. **Priors:** What constraints on the latent space? (sparsity, modularity, causal structure)\n\n**Best bet for breakthrough:**\nCausal discovery + sparse representations + goal-directed environment interaction.\n\nThe causal structure tells you what's semantically related.\nThe sparse representation ensures you can't encode everything — must select.\nThe goal-directed interaction provides the signal for what matters.\n\n**This suggests:** Build a system in an environment where:\n- Interventions are possible (agent can act and see consequences)\n- Temporal structure is rich (succession, causation observable)\n- Goals are learnable (not hardcoded reward)\n\nLet the system discover causal structure through interaction.\nLet the compressor encode causal structure in sparse latents.\nLet the reasoner compose over causal primitives.\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. Can causal structure be learned from passive observation, or are interventions strictly necessary?\n2. What is the minimal inductive bias needed for semantic compression?\n3. Can we combine multiple compression objectives (invariant + predictive + causal) in a single training signal?\n4. How do you evaluate compression quality without downstream tasks?\n5. Is there a fundamental limit on unsupervised semantic compression?\n\n---\n\n## References to Explore\n\n- **InfoGAN** (Chen et al., 2016) — mutual information as regularization\n- **Contrastive Predictive Coding** (Oord et al., 2018) — future prediction as compression\n- **Causal Discovery** (Pearl, Spirtes, Glymour) — do-calculus, PC algorithm\n- **Sparse Autoencoders** (Anthropic, 2024) — monosemantic features in LLMs\n- **World Models / Dreamer** (Hafner et al., 2019, 2023) — world model for RL\n- **Minimum Description Length** (Rissanen, 1978) — compression = learning\n- **Invariant Risk Minimization** (Arjovsky et al., 2019) — invariance as generalization\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774382636378}}
{"type":"message","id":"3fb0f61d","parentId":"52cc3b1a","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:03:56.381Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ostwvin2enrz_3","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# CURRENT GOALS\nLast updated: 2026-03-22 0125\n\n## Active\n- Phase 0 COMPLETE: Sandbox foundation established\n- Phase 1 COMPLETE: Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\n\n## Completed This Session\n\n### Architecture Cross-Analysis ✅\n- Compared Compositional Cognition vs TemporalAttention vs Infant\n- Key finding: all three architectures are compatible and complementary\n- Full analysis: `research/ARCHITECTURE-COMPARISON.md`\n\n### Gap-Decay Synthesis ✅ (derived across 17+ pulses)\n- Session gaps = decay mechanism, not amnesia\n- λ parameter encodes BOTH decay rate AND gap sensitivity threshold\n- TemporalAttention focus_decay + Breakaway gaps = same phenomenon\n- Full synthesis: `research/GAP-DECAY-MAPPING.md`\n\n### LLM-Augmented Pulse ✅\n- pulse.ps1 now calls MiniMax-M2.7 API on each pulse\n- Thinking is coherent and building across pulses\n- Key files: `.llm_key`, `pulse.ps1`\n\n## Phase 1 Advancement: CFI Compression Experiment ✅ (2026-03-24)\n- **New doc:** `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_SYNTHESIS.md`\n- **Ran:** Full experiment comparing freq-only vs CFI-hard on 200 pulses (80/20 split)\n- **Result:** CFI gives +32.9% precision (0.5653 vs 0.4254) BUT loses 92.9% recall\n- **Key finding:** CFI ≥ 0.7 AND freq < 60 is TOO aggressive — pure threshold approach fails\n- **NEW INSIGHT — Constant Format Problem:**\n  - Tokens with freq=160, CFI=1.00 (\"for next instantiation\", \"pulse\", \"completed at:\") are metaprogramming artifacts\n  - CFI=1.00 means perfect prediction, but they appear in EVERY pulse — zero information content\n  - \"Phase 1\" (freq=136, CFI=0.96) is true research trajectory — causal but not constant\n- **Synthesis:** Need THREE-DIMENSIONAL filter: CFI ≥ 0.5 AND freq ∈ [3, 120)\n- **Next experiment:** Hybrid CFI×Freq^0.5 scoring vs binary thresholds\n\n## Pending\n- [ ] Hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment (Strategy C)\n  - Formula: score(T) = CFI(T) × min(1, freq(T)/120)\n  - Test: does this distinguish \"constant format\" (freq≈160, CFI=1) from \"research trajectory\" (freq<120, CFI>0.5)?\n  - Run: 200 pulses, 80/20 split, compare against binary thresholds\n- [ ] Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\n- [ ] Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\n- [ ] Design actual compression network (currently only analyzed text invariants)\n\n## Key Insights from This Session\n\n1. **CFI and frequency are ORTHOGONAL signals** — combine both, don't choose one\n2. **Constant-format tokens** (freq=160, CFI=1) are the trap — they look causal but aren't\n3. **Three-dimensional compression filter**: CFI ≥ 0.5 AND freq ≥ 3 AND freq < 120\n4. **Compression objective for Layer 1 is now concrete**: score(T) = CFI(T) × min(1, freq(T)/120)\n\n## Key Insights from This Session\n\n1. **The gap IS the compression** — session boundaries are temporal hashing\n2. **λ encodes both** — decay rate and gap threshold are the same parameter\n3. **Three architectures, one synthesis** — Infant (catastrophic forgetting), TemporalAttention (focus decay), Breakaway (discontinuity) are complementary, not competing\n4. **Breakaway's unique bet holds** — session gaps as compression is novel and correct\n\n## Notes\n- Breakaway is stateless — each pulse is a fresh reconstruction\n- Gaps between sessions = compression, trust the files\n- Pulse script: active hours check DISABLED (authorized by Zach, 24/7 operation)\n\n\n## Iteration Economics (auto-noted)\n- Pulse takes ~30-35s to execute (LLM call dominates)\n- Fastest effective iteration = 1 pulse per 35-40s (practical floor)\n- 1-min cron = near-optimal for stateless discontinuous agent\n- Idling between pulses is NOT free — it delays convergence linearly\n- For N-iteration convergence-bound tasks: total_time ≈ N * pulse_duration\n- 500k iterations @ 30s each = ~173 days theoretical; @ 1-min = ~347 days\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774382636380}}
