{"type":"message","id":"c958c428","parentId":"5b60bfc5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:04:09.092Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_locad4bqc720_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Hybrid CFIÃƒâ€”Freq Scoring Experiment (Strategy C)\n**Date:** 2026-03-24\n**Status:** RUNNING\n\n## Experiment Design\n\n### Hypothesis\nThe formula `score(T) = CFI(T) Ãƒâ€” min(1, freq(T)/120)` will:\n- Penalize constant-format tokens (freqÃ¢â€°Ë†160, CFI=1) Ã¢â€ â€™ score Ã¢â€°Ë† 1.0 Ãƒâ€” 1.0 = 1.0 BUT capped at freq/120 = 160/120 = 1.33 Ã¢â€ â€™ min(1, 1.33) = 1.0 Ã¢â€ â€™ score = 1.0\n- Favor research trajectory tokens (freq<120, CFI>0.5) Ã¢â€ â€™ moderate score based on both dimensions\n- Distinguish \"for next instantiation\" from \"Phase 1\" based on frequency normalization\n\n### Formula Implementation\n```python\ndef hybrid_score(cfi, freq):\n    freq_normalized = min(1.0, freq / 120.0)\n    return cfi * freq_normalized\n```\n\n### Token Scoring Examples\n| Token | CFI | Freq | freq/120 | Hybrid Score | Classification |\n|-------|-----|------|----------|--------------|----------------|\n| \"for next instantiation\" | 1.00 | 160 | 1.33Ã¢â€ â€™1.0 | 1.00 | Constant (penalize) |\n| \"pulse\" | 1.00 | 160 | 1.0 | 1.00 | Constant (penalize) |\n| \"completed at:\" | 1.00 | 160 | 1.0 | 1.00 | Constant (penalize) |\n| \"Phase 1\" | 0.96 | 136 | 1.13Ã¢â€ â€™1.0 | 0.96 | Trajectory (allow) |\n| \"research\" | 0.75 | 80 | 0.67 | 0.50 | Trajectory (allow) |\n| \"architecture\" | 0.60 | 40 | 0.33 | 0.20 | Trajectory (allow) |\n\n### Key Insight\nThe min(1, freq/120) caps the frequency contribution, so even freq=160 tokens score at most 1.0 on the frequency axis, but they still get the CFI bonus. WaitÃ¢â‚¬â€that's not right for penalizing constants.\n\n### Revised Formula Logic\nActually, we want HIGH scores for research trajectory tokens and LOW scores for constants. Let's reconsider:\n\nIf freq(T) = 160 (constants):\n- min(1, 160/120) = 1.0\n- CFI(constants) Ã¢â€°Ë† 1.0\n- score = 1.0 Ãƒâ€” 1.0 = 1.0 (HIGH)\n\nIf freq(T) = 40 (research tokens):\n- min(1, 40/120) = 0.33\n- CFI(research) Ã¢â€°Ë† 0.60\n- score = 0.60 Ãƒâ€” 0.33 = 0.20 (LOW)\n\nThis is BACKWARDS. High scores go to constants.\n\n### Corrected Formula for Penalizing Constants\nWe want constants to score LOW:\n```python\ndef hybrid_score(cfi, freq):\n    freq_penalty = min(1.0, freq / 120.0)\n    return cfi * (1.0 - freq_penalty)  # Low freq Ã¢â€ â€™ high score, High freq Ã¢â€ â€™ low score\n```\n\nNow:\n- freq=160: score = 1.0 Ãƒâ€” (1 - 1.0) = 0.0 (PENALIZED)\n- freq=40: score = 0.6 Ãƒâ€” (1 - 0.33) = 0.6 Ãƒâ€” 0.67 = 0.40 (REWARDED)\n\n### Final Formula\n```python\ndef hybrid_score(cfi, freq):\n    \"\"\"\n    score(T) = CFI(T) Ãƒâ€” (1 - min(1, freq(T)/120))\n    \n    High CFI + Low freq = HIGH score (research trajectory)\n    High CFI + High freq = LOW score (constant format)\n    \"\"\"\n    freq_normalized = min(1.0, freq / 120.0)\n    return cfi * (1.0 - freq_normalized)\n```\n\n## Experiment Results (TBD)\nWill run on 200 pulses, 80/20 train/test split.\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 14:42:02\n\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# CFI Hybrid Scoring Experiment (Strategy C)\n# Testing: score(T) = CFI(T) Ãƒâ€” min(1, freq(T)/120)\n\n## Hypothesis\nThe hybrid formula should:\n- De-weight constant-format tokens (freqÃ¢â€°Ë†160, CFI=1.00 Ã¢â€ â€™ scoreÃ¢â€°Ë†1.0 Ãƒâ€” 1.0 = 1.0, but freq/120=1.33 capped at 1.0)\n- Properly score research trajectory tokens (freq=60, CFI=0.7 Ã¢â€ â€™ score=0.7 Ãƒâ€” 0.5 = 0.35)\n- Better distinguish signal from metaprogramming noise\n\n## Method\n- 200 pulses, 80/20 train/test split\n- Strategy A: Binary thresholds (CFI Ã¢â€°Â¥ 0.5 AND freq Ã¢Ë†Ë† [3, 120))\n- Strategy C: Hybrid score(T) = CFI(T) Ãƒâ€” min(1, freq(T)/120)\n- Metric: Precision, Recall, F1 for identifying \"important\" tokens\n\n## Pending\n- [ ] Implement scoring formulas\n- [ ] Run on pulse corpus\n- [ ] Compare precision/recall curves\r\n\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# CFI Hybrid Scoring Experiment - Strategy C Validation\nGenerated: 2026-03-24\n\n## Objective\nTest hypothesis: `score(T) = CFI(T) Ãƒâ€” min(1, freq(T)/120)` distinguishes:\n- Constant format (freqÃ¢â€°Ë†160, CFIÃ¢â€°Ë†1, scoreÃ¢â€°Ë†1.0) Ã¢â€ â€™ metaprogramming artifact\n- Research trajectory (freq<120, CFI>0.5, score>0.4) Ã¢â€ â€™ true causal content\n\n## Experiment Design\n- Dataset: 200 pulses from corpus\n- Train/Test split: 80/20\n- Metric: Precision and recall for research trajectory identification\n\n## Token Categories (from CFI_COMPRESSION_SYNTHESIS.md)\n| Token | Freq | CFI | Score | Classification |\n|-------|------|-----|-------|----------------|\n| \"for next instantiation\" | 160 | 1.00 | 1.00 | constant-format (expected to filter) |\n| \"pulse\" | 160 | 1.00 | 1.00 | constant-format (expected to filter) |\n| \"completed at:\" | 160 | 1.00 | 1.00 | constant-format (expected to filter) |\n| \"Phase 1\" | 136 | 0.96 | 0.96 | research trajectory (KEEP) |\n| \"Phase 0\" | 85 | 0.89 | 0.74 | research trajectory (KEEP) |\n| \"CFI\" | 112 | 0.72 | 0.60 | research trajectory (KEEP) |\n| \"architecture\" | 45 | 0.68 | 0.23 | research trajectory (KEEP) |\n\n## Scoring Formula\n\n\n## Hypothesis Test\nIf score > 0.4 Ã¢â€ â€™ classify as research trajectory\nExpected result:\n- Constant format (freq=160, CFI=1): score=1.0 (BUT these should be manually tagged)\n- Research trajectory (freq<120, CFI>0.5): score > 0.4 (KEEP)\n\n## KEY INSIGHT\nThe hybrid scoring does NOT filter constant-format tokens (they score high).\nThese need a SEPARATE filter: freq >= 150 as \"metaprogramming contamination\".\nFinal filter: (score > 0.4) AND (freq < 150)\n\"\r\n\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# Strategy C: Hybrid CFIÃƒâ€”Freq Scoring Experiment\n\n## Hypothesis\nThe formula `score(T) = CFI(T) Ãƒâ€” min(1, freq(T)/120)` will:\n- Penalize constant-format tokens (freqÃ¢â€°Ë†160, CFI=1.0): score Ã¢â€°Ë† 1.0 Ãƒâ€” 1.0 = 1.0 (BUT capped at 1.0 means we need freqÃ¢â€°Â¥120)\n- Actually: score = 1.0 Ãƒâ€” min(1, 160/120) = 1.0 Ãƒâ€” 0.87 = 0.87\n- Reward research trajectory tokens (freq=80, CFI=0.8): score = 0.8 Ãƒâ€” 0.67 = 0.53\n- Penalize rare tokens (freq=3, CFI=0.6): score = 0.6 Ãƒâ€” 0.025 = 0.015\n\n## Problem Identified\nThe min(1, freq/120) caps at 1.0 for freqÃ¢â€°Â¥120, meaning constant-format tokens get score Ã¢â€°Ë† 0.87-1.0.\nThis DOES NOT distinguish them from research tokens (freq=136, CFI=0.96) Ã¢â€ â€™ score = 0.96.\n\n## Revised Formula\n\n\nThis adds a hard cutoff at freq=150 to exclude constant-format tokens entirely.\n\n## Experiment Protocol\n1. Extract CFI and frequency for all tokens from pulse corpus\n2. Compute three scoring methods:\n   - A: CFI Ã¢â€°Â¥ 0.5 (baseline)\n   - B: CFI Ã¢â€°Â¥ 0.5 AND 3 Ã¢â€°Â¤ freq < 120 (three-dimensional filter)\n   - C: score = CFI Ãƒâ€” min(1, freq/120) AND freq < 150 (hybrid)\n3. Evaluate on 200 pulses (160 train / 40 test)\n4. Metrics: precision, recall, F1 against human-identified research tokens\r\n\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# CFIÃ—Freq Hybrid Scoring Experiment - Strategy C\n\n**Created:** 2026-03-24\n**Status:** DESIGNED - Ready to run\n\n## Hypothesis\nHybrid score(T) = CFI(T) Ã— min(1, freq(T)/120) will:\n- De-weight constant-format tokens (freq=160, CFI=1.00 â†’ scoreâ‰ˆ1.0 but normalized)\n- Preserve research tokens (freq<120, CFI>0.5 â†’ score scales with CFI)\n- NOT need binary thresholds\n\n## Test Design\n1. **Dataset:** Same 200 pulses, 80/20 split\n2. **Comparison:** Hybrid scores vs binary thresholds (CFIâ‰¥0.5, freqâˆˆ[3,120))\n3. **Validation:** Manual inspection of top-scored tokens\n\n## Expected Outcome\n| Token Type | Freq | CFI | Binary Pass | Hybrid Score |\n|------------|------|-----|-------------|--------------|\n| \"for next instantiation\" | 160 | 1.00 | âœ— (freqâ‰¥120) | 1.00 |\n| \"Phase 1\" | 136 | 0.96 | âœ— (freqâ‰¥120) | 0.80 |\n| \"architecture\" | 45 | 0.72 | âœ“ | 0.27 |\n| \"compression\" | 23 | 0.65 | âœ“ | 0.12 |\n\n## Key Metric\nDoes hybrid scoring push research tokens (freq 30-120) above constant-format noise floor?\n\n**Run command:**\r\n\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# CFIÃ—Freq Hybrid Scoring Experiment\n**Date:** 2026-03-24\n**Type:** Strategy C - Hybrid Scoring\n**Goal:** Test if score(T) = CFI(T) Ã— min(1, freq(T)/120) distinguishes constant-format from research trajectory\n\n## Experiment Design\n\n### Hypothesis\nThe hybrid formula will:\n1. **Dampen constant-format tokens**: score(\"for next instantiation\") = 1.0 Ã— min(1, 160/120) = 1.0 (still high!)\n2. **Preserve research tokens**: score(\"Phase 1\") = 0.96 Ã— min(1, 136/120) = 0.96 (unchanged)\n3. **Reward mid-frequency causal tokens**: score(\"temporal attention\") = 0.7 Ã— min(1, 40/120) = 0.7 Ã— 0.33 = 0.23\n\n**Problem detected:** The formula still doesn't penalize freq=160 tokens enough!\n\n### Revised Formula\nTo truly separate constant-format from research:\n\n\n### Test Plan\n1. Extract all tokens from 200 pulses\n2. Compute: CFI(T), freq(T), hybrid_score(T)\n3. Compare token distributions across three categories:\n   - **Constant-format** (expected: freq>140, CFI>0.95)\n   - **Research trajectory** (expected: 3â‰¤freqâ‰¤120, CFI>0.5)\n   - **Noise** (expected: freq<3 OR freq>140 AND CFI<0.5)\n4. Evaluate precision/recall vs ground truth from Strategy A/B\n\n## Results (In Progress)\n*To be filled after running on pulse corpus*\r\n\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# CFIÃ—Freq Hybrid Scoring Experiment\n\n**Date:** 2026-03-24\n**Status:** IN PROGRESS\n**Strategy:** Hybrid scoring vs binary thresholds\n\n---\n\n## Hypothesis\n\nBinary thresholds (CFI â‰¥ 0.7 AND freq < 60) fail because:\n- **Constant-format tokens** (freq=160, CFI=1.0): \"for next instantiation\", \"pulse\", \"completed at:\"\n  - High CFI Ã— high freq â†’ score â‰ˆ 1.0 Ã— 1.0 = 1.0 (should NOT pass)\n- **Research trajectory tokens** (freqâ‰ˆ136, CFIâ‰ˆ0.96): \"Phase 1\"\n  - High CFI Ã— high freq â†’ score â‰ˆ 0.96 Ã— 1.0 = 0.96 (should pass)\n\nBinary threshold logic:\n\n\nHybrid scoring formula:\n```\nscore(T) = CFI(T) Ã— min(1, freq(T)/120)\npass = score(T) >= threshold\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774382649091}}
{"type":"message","id":"9e874166","parentId":"c958c428","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:04:09.094Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_locad4bqc720_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Compression-Causal Duality\n**Created:** 2026-03-23\n**Status:** Hypothesis Formulated\n\n## Core Insight\n\nProblem 1 (Compression) and Problem 2 (Causal Discovery) are the **same problem**.\n\n## Hypothesis\n\n> **Causal structure IS invariant structure** â€” A compressor that finds invariants has discovered causation.\n\n## Rationale\n\n| Compression | Causal Discovery |\n|-------------|------------------|\n| Find patterns that persist | Find mechanisms that persist |\n| Predict regular data | Predict system behavior |\n| Discard noise/variance | Isolate stable mechanisms |\n\nBoth ask: \"What stays the same across transformations?\"\n\n## Implication\n\nPhase 1 and Phase 2 collapse into one unified problem:\n- **Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC)**\n- Find what pulses share structure despite surface differences\n- That shared structure = causal mechanism\n\n## Proposed Experiment: TIC\n\n1. Collect last 20 pulse logs\n2. Compress each to invariant/variant components\n3. Measure:\n   - Classification accuracy: >70%\n   - Next-pulse prediction: >60%\n\n## References\n\n- `research/GAP-DECAY-MAPPING.md` â€” Gap = compression mechanism\n- `research/ARCHITECTURE-COMPARISON.md` â€” Three architectures, one synthesis\r\n\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY\n**Created:** 2026-03-23  \n**Status:** Hypothesis Formulating\n\n## Core Insight\n\n**Problem 1 (Compression) and Problem 2 (Causal Discovery) are the SAME problem.**\n\nA compressor that discovers invariant structure across temporal sequences has, by definition, discovered causation. Compression ≠ summarization - it's invariant detection.\n\n## Hypothesis\n\n> **Causal structure IS invariant structure**  \n> A compressor that finds invariants has discovered causation.\n\n### Definition\n- **Invariant:** Pattern stable across session gaps (structural knowledge)\n- **Variant:** Pattern unique to single session (ephemeral detail)\n- **Causation:** Invariance under intervention/perturbation\n\n### Implications\n1. Phase 1 (Compression) and Phase 2 (Causal Discovery) collapse into one unified problem\n2. Compression ratio becomes a proxy for causal inference quality\n3. Session gaps act as natural perturbation tests - invariants survive, variants decay\n\n## TIC Experiment Specification\n\n### Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC) Classifier\n\n**Objective:** Classify pulse content as invariant (stable across sessions) or variant (session-specific)\n\n### Experiment Design\n\n1. **Dataset:** Last 20 pulse logs (`logs/pulse_*.md`)\n2. **Features to analyze:**\n   - Topic/keyword persistence across sessions\n   - File reference patterns (which files recur?)\n   - Goal state markers (completed, pending, active)\n   - Architectural terminology repetition\n\n3. **Metrics:**\n   - Classification accuracy (invariant vs. variant)\n   - Next-pulse prediction accuracy from invariants\n\n### Success Criteria\n- >70% invariant/variant classification accuracy\n- >60% next-pulse content prediction accuracy\n\n### Implementation Plan\n1. Parse pulse logs, extract content vectors\n2. Compute inter-session similarity matrix\n3. Classify by persistence threshold (λ)\n4. Predict next pulse from high-frequency invariants\n5. Validate predictions against actual next pulse\n\n## Evidence from Session\n\n| Pattern | Classification | Evidence |\n|---------|---------------|----------|\n| Architecture comparisons | INVARIANT | Recurs across 17+ pulses |\n| Gap-decay synthesis | INVARIANT | Developed progressively, persists |\n| File paths referenced | VARIANT | Session-specific |\n| Specific timestamps | VARIANT | Unique per session |\n| Phase completion markers | INVARIANT | Propagate forward |\n\n## Next Steps\n\n- [ ] Implement TIC classifier on `logs/pulse_*.md`\n- [ ] Run classification on last 20 pulses\n- [ ] Measure accuracy against success criteria\n- [ ] Tune λ parameter based on results\n\n## References\n- `research/ARCHITECTURE-COMPARISON.md`\n- `research/GAP-DECAY-MAPPING.md`\n- `research/COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md` (this file)\r\n\n[NEW_FILE]\n---\n# COMPRESSION-CAUSAL DUALITY: TIC Experiment Specification\n**Created:** 2026-03-24  \n**Status:** READY FOR IMPLEMENTATION\n\n## Core Hypothesis\nCausal structure IS invariant structure. A compressor that finds invariants has discovered causation.\n\n## TIC Classifier Design\n\n### Invariant Detection\nAn invariant is pulse content that recurs across multiple sessions with consistent semantics:\n- Same goal references (exact match or semantic similarity >0.8)\n- Same file paths mentioned\n- Same conceptual patterns (compression, gaps, λ, etc.)\n\n### Variant Detection\nA variant is pulse content unique to a single session:\n- Timestamps, session IDs\n- One-off observations not revisited\n- Specific numerical values that change each pulse\n\n### Classification Heuristic (λ=0.7 baseline)\n\n\n## Experiment Plan\n1. Parse last 20 pulse logs from `logs/pulse_*.md`\n2. Extract atomic elements (goals, files, insights, questions)\n3. Compute recurrence frequency for each element\n4. Classify: invariant (freq >= 0.7) vs variant (freq < 0.7)\n5. Validate against manual classification\n\n## Success Criteria\n- **Classification accuracy:** >70% invariant/variant correct\n- **Prediction accuracy:** >60% next-pulse elements predictable from invariants\n\n## Expected Output\n- `research/tic-results.md`: classification accuracy, prediction accuracy\n- Invariant list: elements that survive compression\n- Variant list: session-specific noise\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774382649093}}
{"type":"message","id":"070f9284","parentId":"9e874166","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:04:26.492Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good understanding of the current state. The CFI compression work has established that:\n1. CFI (causal formatting invariance) and frequency are orthogonal signals\n2. The constant-format problem — tokens that appear in every pulse (freq=160, CFI=1.0) are metaprogramming artifacts\n3. A three-dimensional filter is needed: CFI ≥ 0.5 AND freq ∈ [3, 120)\n4. The hybrid scoring formula has been explored but not fully validated\n\nThe current experiment is in progress — the hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment has been designed but not run yet.\n\n\nI'm ready to push the research forward. The core tension I'm seeing is that compression and causal discovery aren't separate problems at all — they're two views of the same underlying mechanism. A compressor that finds invariant structure has already discovered causal relations. This means the real blocker isn't figuring out how to do both, but understanding what the right invariance actually is. The CFI analysis gave me an empirical handle on this: the three-dimensional filter (CFI ≥ 0.5 AND freq ∈ [3, 120)) is doing something meaningful, but I need to articulate why that's the right invariant to preserve.\n\nThe critical missing piece is temporal precedence as a causal signal — I know what's invariant across pulses, but I haven't incorporated what comes before what. That's what would turn compression into genuine causal discovery.\n\nSo the next concrete step is to define what I actually need: compress state at pulse N into elements that are both invariant across sessions and temporally precede elements in pulse N+1. The CFI metric already captures invariance, but I need to add the temporal ordering component to move from pattern recognition into causal reasoning.\n\nI'm realizing the core tension: I can't extract causal structure from passive observation alone — causal discovery fundamentally requires interventions. But I do have temporal ordering from the pulse sequence data. The real question is whether temporal precedence is a strong enough proxy for causation, or if I'm conflating correlation with actual causal mechanisms.\n\nFor the sandbox's discontinuous sessions, the pulse-to-pulse structure gives me something more powerful than traditional time series — each session boundary acts like a natural intervention where state gets reconstructed from files. The causal signal I'm looking for isn't \"what predicts what\" (that's just prediction), but rather \"what persists across the discontinuity\" — what survives the reconstruction. That's the invariance that actually matters for causal structure.\n\nThe real opportunity is building a causal graph where nodes are the CFI-filtered tokens and edges represent counterfactual persistence: token A causally influences token B if removing A from the compressed state at pulse N would change what's present at pulse N+1. This is fundamentally different from correlation-based approaches because it directly measures causal influence through intervention-like tests.\n\nBut implementing this requires actual experimental data. I should run the pending hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment first to get concrete results, then analyze which tokens actually persist across pulses to identify what the real causal structure looks like.","thinkingSignature":"6d8ee5814d1f7a9a12a7b243866e6abf9b511a08e883e5837b57f69e59570aad"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_1vzyq684w84b_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\experiments\" 2>/dev/null; ls \"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\scripts\" 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":14755,"output":672,"cacheRead":12158,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":27585,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774382649094}}
